{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.44,0,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115336"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10593"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10025"},{"type":"tags","id":"10078"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24693"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115336"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first two steps of the urea cycle occur in the mitochondria. The final step occurs in the cytosol.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding urea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is synthesised almost exclusively in the liver","It is neurotoxic","It is primarily excreted through the lungs","It is a byproduct of carbohydrate metabolism","It is stored in the muscles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is synthesised almost exclusively in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E. The urea cycle converts ammonia, a toxic byproduct of protein metabolism, into urea, a less toxic compound that can be safely excreted by the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is neurotoxic\u003C/strong\u003E. Urea itself is not neurotoxic. Elevated levels of urea in the blood - uraemia, can lead to symptoms affecting the nervous system, but this is due to the accumulation of other toxins rather than urea itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is primarily excreted through the lungs\u003C/strong\u003E. Urea is primarily excreted by the kidneys in urine. The lungs are not involved in the excretion of urea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is a byproduct of carbohydrate metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E. Urea is a byproduct of protein metabolism, not carbohydrate metabolism. It results from the breakdown of amino acids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is stored in the muscles\u003C/strong\u003E. Urea is not stored in the muscles; it is transported in the blood to the kidneys for excretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urea is synthesised in the liver as part of the urea cycle.","Urea is not neurotoxic; it is a waste product of protein metabolism excreted by the kidneys.","Elevated urea levels can indicate renal dysfunction but are not directly harmful to the nervous system."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 71, pg. 873.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. Hoboken: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Amino Acid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Apr 1;13(4):a040584. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040584. PMID: 33795250; PMCID: PMC8015690.","Ling ZN, Jiang YF, Ru JN, Lu JH, Ding B, Wu J. Amino acid metabolism in health and disease. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2023 Sep 13;8(1):345. doi: 10.1038/s41392-023-01569-3. PMID: 37699892; PMCID: PMC10497558."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97339"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97339"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:23:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:23:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10593"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115336"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc